{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496594"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:51:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:51:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1388"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1388"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.05,0.61,0.07,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1388"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86579"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1388"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1388"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70861"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"737"},{"type":"tags","id":"2453"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"5901"},{"type":"tags","id":"5943"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1071"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1395"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1511"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28382"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86579"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of progressive weakness in her legs. She is now unable to walk. She was unwell with a diarrhoeal illness three weeks ago but recovered after five days. She has no medical history and uses the oral contraceptive pill for contraception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell but her vital signs are within normal limits. Her legs are weak bilaterally (2/5 power). She has absent patella and ankle reflexes but her plantar reflex is down-going. She has a stocking distribution sensory loss in her feet to both pain and vibration sense.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following lumbar puncture findings would support the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oligoclonal bands","Absent protein","Albuminocytologic dissociation","Bacterial organisms","Herpes simplex virus detected"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture described is suggestive of Guillain-Barre Syndrome (GBS), which is an acute immune-mediated polyneuropathy characterised by acute, progressive, and relatively symmetrical weakness, with absent or depressed deep tendon reflexes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlbuminocytologic dissociation\u003C/strong\u003E is a hallmark finding in GBS, where there is elevated cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) protein with a normal CSF white blood cell count. This finding is present in 50-66% of patients after one week and in over 75% after the third week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOligoclonal bands\u003C/strong\u003E are more commonly associated with multiple sclerosis and are not a typical finding in GBS. While they can occasionally be present in GBS, they are not diagnostic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsent protein\u003C/strong\u003E in the CSF would not support a diagnosis of GBS, as elevated protein is expected due to the breakdown of the blood-nerve barrier.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial organisms\u003C/strong\u003E in the CSF would suggest a bacterial meningitis, which is not consistent with the clinical presentation of GBS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes simplex virus detected\u003C/strong\u003E in the CSF would indicate a viral infection, such as herpes simplex encephalitis, which presents with different clinical features, including altered mental status and seizures, rather than the progressive weakness seen in GBS.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Guillain-Barre Syndrome (GBS) is characterised by progressive weakness, areflexia, and often follows a recent infection.","Albuminocytologic dissociation, where there is elevated protein with normal white cell count in cerebrospinal fluid, is a key diagnostic finding in GBS.","Oligoclonal bands are more commonly associated with multiple sclerosis rather than GBS."],"references":["Willison HJ, Jacobs BC, van Doorn PA. Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome. Lancet. 2016;388(10045):717-27 Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26948435/","Yuki N, Hartung HP. Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome. N Engl J Med. 2012 Jun 14;366(24):2294-304. doi: 10.1056/NEJMra1114525. Erratum in: N Engl J Med. 2012 Oct 25;367(17):1673. PMID: 22694000. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22694000/","Nguyen TP, Taylor RS. Guillain-Barre Syndrome. [Updated 2023 Feb 7]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532254/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70861"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1388"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70861"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-22T15:06:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-22T15:07:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1388"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86579"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes